==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relativistic mass equation
<hw>Rel`a*tiv*ist"ic mass e*qua"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<fld>(physics)</fld> <def>an equation expressing the mass of an object
as a function of its velocity: as the velocity <it>v</it> of an object
increases, its mass <it>m</it> increases from its rest mass
<it>m</it><sub>0</sub> according to the equation: <mathex>m =
m<sub>0</sub>/<root>1 - v<exp>2</exp>/c<exp>2</exp></root></mathex>

where <it>c</it> is the speed of light in a vacuum. If the speed of an
object were to become equal to that of light, it can be seen that the
mass would be infinite, from which it follows that nothing can
accelerate up to or beyond the speed of light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The theoretical possibility that there are particles
which always move faster than light cannot at present be disproved and
is not denied by this equation; in such a case, the <ex>relativistic
mass equation</ex> asserts that such particles can never decelerate to
or below the speed of light. Such hypothetical particles are referred to
as <col><b>tachyons</b></col>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>relativity</ent>⟦br⟧
